Air Quality Analysis Report

Youwei Hu

2025-04-29

Introduction

The Air Quality Dataset from the UCI Machine Learning Repository contains initially contains 9471 hourly measurements collected in an Italian city from March 2004 to February 2005. It includes concentrations of key air pollutants (e.g., tin oxide, titania, tungsten oxides, benzene) and meteorological conditions (temperature, relative humidity, absolute humidity).

Analysis Objectives:

  • Data Cleaning: Handle missing values and standardize numeric variables.

  • Exploratory Analysis: Generate descriptive statistics and visualize trends in the data.

  • Model Building: Split the data into training and testing sets and build linear regression models to predict pollutant levels.

  • Evaluation: Summarize findings and evaluate model performance.

Data Cleaning

In this section, I use reproducible code with the here package to load the cleaned dataset (data_clean.rds), which was generated in an R script named clean_data.R. This script performs initial data cleaning, including creating a new datetime variable and removing extra rows and columns that contain only missing values.

Descriptive Statistics

Visualization of Correlation

Correlation matrix plot is performed to visualize the relationships between numeric variables and identify potential multicollinearity issues and guide further analysis. Correlation Heatmap

High correlation among pollutant sensor readings suggests that they capture similar environmental trends. NOx and NO2 levels are strongly related, implying they can be used interchangeably in some models. Temperature and NOx levels have an inverse relationship, which could be important for air pollution forecasting. Humidity’s role in air pollution appears minimal based on this dataset.

Linear Regression Analysis

I split the data into training and testing sets using an 80/20 time-based split and develop a linear regression model to predict benzene concentration (C6H6.GT.). First, I fit a full model incorporating all regressors.

Conclusion

In this report, we performed an exploratory analysis of the Air Quality Dataset. The steps included:

Data Cleaning: Combining date and time into a datetime variable, removing unused columns, and handling missing values. Descriptive Analysis: Presenting summary statistics in a formatted table. Visualization: Creating a time series plot of benzene concentration. Modeling: Developing a linear regression model to predict benzene levels based on meteorological variables.
